=== Location ===
* {{jalink|Gifu Prefecture|Q131277}}{{jalink|Kakamigahara|Q641491}}{{jalink|Mii-cho (Kakamigahara)|Q131870038|Mii-cho}} 5-8

=== Transport ===
* Kakamigahara Fureai Bus (Inaba line), get off at "Mii-cho Kominkan-mae," about 3 minutes on foot.

=== Okunomiya ===
[[File:Mii Shrine at Mount Mii 2010-12-19.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Okunomiya of Mii Shrine near the summit of Mt. Mii]]
Near the summit of Mt. Mii, where the former shrine once stood. It was divided from Mii Shrine after the fall of Mii Castle (date unknown).

Mt. Mii also has ritual sites associated with iwakura worship and many excavated artifacts, as well as a kofun (Miiyama Kofun).

=== Deity ===
* Mii-no-kami
=== Address ===
* Government land without lot number, Naka, Kakamigahara (near summit of Mt. Mii)

=== Miiike Ryujin Shrine ===
A separate shrine of Mii Shrine, also called "Mii Shrine Ikenomiya" or "Miiike Ryujin Shrine." Mii Pond at the foot of Mt. Mii is said to have been dug by Mii-no-kami and is an oxbow-lake remnant of the old Kiso River channel.

In 1929, during landfill work around Mii Pond, a worker operating an irrigation pump reportedly entered a trance and moved like a dragon crawling on the ground; after this and related experiences, a small shrine was established by enshrining the spirit of Mii Shrine together with a dragon deity.{{Sfn|前渡歴史保存会|2024|p=39}} The present building was reconstructed in 1976 using part of old materials.

=== Deity ===
* Dragon deity (Miiike Ryujin / Miike Ryujin)

=== Precinct shrines ===
* Suijin
* Kappa shrine

=== Address ===
* {{jalink|Miiyamacho|Q133214736}}, Kakamigahara (about 15 minutes on foot from Mii Shrine)

