'''Mii Shrine''' (みいじんじゃ) is a Shinto shrine in {{ill|lt=Kakamigahara|Q641491|WD=Q641491|1=Kakamigahara}}, {{ill|lt=Gifu Prefecture|Q131277|WD=Q131277|1=Gifu Prefecture}} (former Kakamigun, Mino Province).

=== Overview ===
It is listed in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyocho|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}. Mii-no-kami is worshiped as a deity of trees, water, and safe childbirth. The area is rich in groundwater, and Kakamigahara's water-source facilities are nearby. Historically, {{ill|lt=Mount Mii|Q11354265|WD=Q11354265|1=Mount Mii}} itself was considered part of the shrine precinct.

Originally the local tutelary shrine of Mii Village (Saraki-mura), it is now regarded as the tutelary shrine of the Inaba area of Kakamigahara. It is one of the city's five {{ill|lt=Kinpeisha|Q119929592|WD=Q119929592|1=Kinpei-sha}} shrines.

=== History ===
The founding date is unknown. Tradition says the original shrine stood on the south slope of Mt. Mii and later moved to the summit. In the Sengoku period, {{ill|lt=Mii Castle|Q11354255|WD=Q11354255|1=Miiyama Castle}} was built on the mountain by Toki-affiliated forces, and the shrine was moved to its current otabisho-area location at the foot of the mountain. A portion of the shrine was also divided and became Tenjin Shrine in Kaminakaya.

Mii Castle fell in 1548 during conflict between the Toki and Saito sides and was abandoned.

The current honden, noritoden, and haiden were completed in 1941.<ref name="mii">Shikinaikinpei Mii Jinja guide booklet.</ref> On December 18, 1952, it was designated a Kinpeisha by the Gifu Prefectural Association of Shinto Shrines.{{sfn|木村|1997|p=73}}

A ritual called ''sakaura shinji'' is held on the first Sunday of April: sake is poured into a bamboo segment with a small hole, sealed with paper, purified, and cast into a pond; if it sinks, the year is expected to be rainy and abundant, and if it floats, drought and poor harvest are expected.

